Russian TV actor responds to accusations of 'LGBT propaganda and feminism'
The actor of the Russian TV series Chiki, whose creators have been accused of "propaganda of LGBT and feminism," has responded to the film's claims.
The authors "understood the urgency of the issues raised and did not want to offend anyone," American Stephen Thomas Oxner said in an interview with The Rise.
"It seems to me that this is a story about the power and general aspects of human life.
This has nothing to do with LGBT and feminism," said the actor, who played the father of a boy who dressed in women's clothing.
He stressed that he was "proud of the work" and did not consider it propaganda.
At the same time, added the American, he is frightened by the reaction of some people to the storyline of the series: for example, there was a case when "a person in a deep breath shot a film set and said that it was all untrue."
"Then on a couple of occasions we met disgruntled locals who didn't understand what we were doing.
But we were open, so the people who first came forward with claims began to help us," he concluded.
The shooting incident, the publication explains, occurred in September 2019 in Kabardino-Balkaria: a drunk man attacked a vehicle of a film crew with a weapon, after which he was detained by police officers.
Earlier it was reported that the public commissioner for the protection of the family, Olga Baranets, sent a complaint to the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Roskomnadzor against the more.tv service that hosted the Russian series "Chiki."
Baranez accused the creators of the series of "propaganda of non-traditional sexual relations and feminism," drawing attention to the fact that the main characters of the film work as prostitutes, and the series itself contains "scenes of physical and psychological violence."
The ombudsman was also outraged that "a lot of attention was paid in the series to the homosexual sexual orientation" of the minor character.
The comedy drama "Chiki" tells about three prostitutes who started a new life and opened a business on the advice of a friend.
